15/02/2005
STRASBOURG, France -- The Council of Europe's arm for fighting racism, the European Commission Against Racism and Intolerance (ECRI), published a series of country monitoring reports Tuesday (15 February), including reports on Bosnia and Herzegovina (BiH), Macedonia and Turkey. According to the commission, problems of direct and indirect discrimination are pervasive in education, employment, housing and access to health services in BiH. Regarding Macedonia, the report cited concerns over the situation of the Roma minority. As for Turkey, ECRI found that in spite of reforms, gaps remain in the constitution and in criminal, civil and administrative laws. (CoE Web site - 15/02/05)
